The time my client almost bought a house that had burned down🤯🔥

Going into this deal, my client and I suspected nothing was wrong. The seller had not disclosed the scorched state of the house beforehand, and we certainly didn’t think to ask. I was told the appraiser had to do a last-minute inspection, and I thought nothing of it.

Lo and behold, when my client was about to sign, I got a phone call from the appraiser saying that the house was no longer there - it had burned down completely! And when I asked the seller about it, he had the nerve to say it was “just a kitchen fire.” Needless to say, the deal did not happen. 

What did I learn from this? Anyone involved financially in the deal could be a liar, so you can ONLY trust yourself and your own due diligence to make sure the deal is right. 

#realestatefail #realestatelesson #realestateinvesting #privatemoneylender #realestatedeal

This is how you can do it step by step:

1. Research and Plan:Explore different property types (duplex, triplex, etc.) and areas that interest you. Consider the local market, property prices, rental demand, and financing options.

2. Secure Financing:Get pre-approved for a mortgage or explore financing options suitable for first-time homebuyers or real estate investors.

3. Find a Suitable Property: Look for a property that fits your criteria, such as a multi-unit building or a house with rentable space. Consider factors like location, condition, and potential rental income.

4. Purchase the Property:Once you find the right property, make an offer and close the deal. Ensure you understand the legal and financial obligations involved in buying a property.

5. Move In and Rent Out: Occupy one unit while renting out the others. Screen potential tenants carefully, set competitive rental rates, and manage the rental agreements professionally.

6. Manage the Property: Maintain the property, handle tenant concerns, and keep up with landlord responsibilities while living on-site.

7. Evaluate and Refine: Continuously assess your house hacking strategy. Make adjustments to maximize rental income or explore other opportunities to expand your real estate portfolio.

Remember, success in house hacking requires a good understanding of real estate investing, property management, and a willingness to take on the responsibilities of a landlord.

💰Here’s how the wealthy leverage property investments to minimize taxes👇

It’s called accelerated depreciation, which is a tax strategy that allows businesses to recover the cost of an asset more quickly than traditional straight-line depreciation. 

Instead of spreading the cost evenly over the asset’s useful life, accelerated depreciation frontloads the deductions, providing larger tax benefits in the earlier years of an asset’s use.

With this method, real estate investors can strategically offset income with real estate gains, creating a tax-efficient financial strategy. 

Savvy investors take it a step further, establishing trusts that span generations, ensuring a legacy of financial empowerment without the burden of taxes. 

Remember to always consult your CPA to determine the best decisions for your situation.

#wealthbuilding #realestateinvestingtips #accelerateddepreciation

💰ROI vs. NOI — Knowing the difference between these two metrics will set you up for real estate success🔥

ROI is a broader metric used to assess the overall performance and profitability of an investment. It takes into account the change in value over time and is often used for various types of investments, not just real estate.

NOI provides valuable insights into the financial health and potential profitability of a real estate investment. It’s specifically focused on the operational aspects of a real estate property, and it doesn’t include financing costs or taxes.

Calculating NOI is important in property valuation, investment analysis, financing considerations, ongoing performance monitoring, market comparisons, and lease negotiations. 

Use this knowledge to help you along the path to building your real estate empire💪

#realestateinvesting #realestateeducation #realestateinvestor

How to buy multiple properties with the same money👇

Savvy real estate investors use HELOCs to leverage the equity in their properties to access funds for more properties.

Here’s how it works: They buy a property at a discount, take out a HELOC on that property, and use the initial investment to acquire another property. 

Unlike a traditional loan, a HELOC gives you a revolving line of credit, allowing you to borrow, repay, and borrow again during the draw period. 

And if you’re playing the game right, you’ll be renting out your properties to cover the payment of the HELOC.

In order to qualify for a HELOC, you need a low debt-to-income (DTI) ratio, proof of income, a solid credit score, and your property must have equity.

To determine whether or not a HELOC could be right for you, consider location, market trends, potential rental income, and potential for property appreciation. Always do your research.🔥

🤑The ONLY get rich quick scheme that works👇

You guessed it — there’s no such thing as a get rich quick scheme that works. Why not? Because the real wealth that you’re looking to build takes years of working hard and working smart.

🏚️Don’t make this common rookie investor mistake👇

Many new investors want to follow the advice of big media figures and invest immediately in big multi-family properties. 

While multi family properties are excellent investments, it’s not wise to jump in right away. Before you start managing a 10-20 unit property, you should invest in your own house. 

Know what it’s like to own a house first — the repairs, maintenance, miscellaneous costs for upkeep… it’s a big undertaking for even a single-family property, and you could get way in over your head if you’re trying to tackle something big. 

Make sure you’re prepared to manage one unit before diving into multiple units.

💰Get rich by buying industrial land👇

Industrial land refers to designated zones for industrial activities, set aside by local governments. These areas support manufacturing, processing, and distribution operations.

Why is this good to invest in? Now that we're in the digital/AI era, this land is mostly abandoned, especially in inner cities. 

This creates a massive opportunity for investors, because the government cannot make money off of unused land.

So to try to make tax money off of this land, the government will incentivize investors like you to buy and repurpose the land into office spaces, retail stores, apartment complexes, etc.

If you see abandoned industrial lands or buildings around your town, start researching how you can acquire them. 

Always be sure to do your research, and remember this is a long-term investment game.🔥
